[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:git-hooks/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Like many other Version Control Systems, Git has a way to fire off custom scripts when certain important actions occur.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] There are two groups of these hooks: client-side and server-side.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Client-side hooks are triggered by operations such as committing and merging, while server-side hooks run on network operations such as receiving pushed commits.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use these hooks for all sorts of reasons.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The hooks are all stored in the `hooks` subdirectory of the Git directory.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] When you initialize a new repository with `git init`, Git populates the hooks directory with a bunch of example scripts, many of which are useful by themselves; but they also document the input values of each script.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] All the examples are written as shell scripts, with some Perl thrown in, but any properly named executable scripts will work fine – you can write them in Ruby or Python or whatever language you are familiar with.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If you want to use the bundled hook scripts, you’ll have to rename them; their file names all end with `.sample`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] To enable a hook script, put a file in the `hooks` subdirectory of your `.git` directory that is named appropriately (without any extension) and is executable.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] From that point forward, it should be called.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] We’ll cover most of the major hook filenames here.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This section splits them into committing-workflow hooks, email-workflow scripts, and everything else.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The first four hooks have to do with the committing process.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `pre-commit` hook is run first, before you even type in a commit message.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It’s used to inspect the snapshot that’s about to be committed, to see if you’ve forgotten something, to make sure tests run, or to examine whatever you need to inspect in the code.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Exiting non-zero from this hook aborts the commit, although you can bypass it with `git commit --no-verify`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can do things like check for code style (run `lint` or something equivalent), check for trailing whitespace (the default hook does exactly this), or check for appropriate documentation on new methods.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `prepare-commit-msg` hook is run before the commit message editor is fired up but after the default message is created.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It lets you edit the default message before the commit author sees it.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This hook takes a few parameters: the path to the file that holds the commit message so far, the type of commit, and the commit SHA-1 if this is an amended commit.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This hook generally isn’t useful for normal commits; rather, it’s good for commits where the default message is auto-generated, such as templated commit messages, merge commits, squashed commits, and amended commits.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You may use it in conjunction with a commit template to programmatically insert information.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `commit-msg` hook takes one parameter, which again is the path to a temporary file that contains the commit message written by the developer.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If this script exits non-zero, Git aborts the commit process, so you can use it to validate your project state or commit message before allowing a commit to go through.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] In the last section of this chapter, we’ll demonstrate using this hook to check that your commit message is conformant to a required pattern.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] After the entire commit process is completed, the `post-commit` hook runs.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It doesn’t take any parameters, but you can easily get the last commit by running `git log -1 HEAD`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Generally, this script is used for notification or something similar.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can set up three client-side hooks for an email-based workflow.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] They’re all invoked by the `git am` command, so if you aren’t using that command in your workflow, you can safely skip to the next section.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If you’re taking patches over email prepared by `git format-patch`, then some of these may be helpful to you.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The first hook that is run is `applypatch-msg`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It takes a single argument: the name of the temporary file that contains the proposed commit message.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Git aborts the patch if this script exits non-zero.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use this to make sure a commit message is properly formatted, or to normalize the message by having the script edit it in place.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The next hook to run when applying patches via `git am` is `pre-applypatch`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Somewhat confusingly, it is run *after* the patch is applied but before a commit is made, so you can use it to inspect the snapshot before making the commit.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can run tests or otherwise inspect the working tree with this script.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If something is missing or the tests don’t pass, exiting non-zero aborts the `git am` script without committing the patch.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The last hook to run during a `git am` operation is `post-applypatch`, which runs after the commit is made.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use it to notify a group or the author of the patch you pulled in that you’ve done so.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can’t stop the patching process with this script.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `pre-rebase` hook runs before you rebase anything and can halt the process by exiting non-zero.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use this hook to disallow rebasing any commits that have already been pushed.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The example `pre-rebase` hook that Git installs does this, although it makes some assumptions that may not match with your workflow.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `post-rewrite` hook is run by commands that replace commits, such as `git commit --amend` and `git rebase` (though not by `git filter-branch`).
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Its single argument is which command triggered the rewrite, and it receives a list of rewrites on `stdin`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This hook has many of the same uses as the `post-checkout` and `post-merge` hooks.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] After you run a successful `git checkout`, the `post-checkout` hook runs; you can use it to set up your working directory properly for your project environment.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This may mean moving in large binary files that you don’t want source controlled, auto-generating documentation, or something along those lines.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `post-merge` hook runs after a successful `merge` command.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use it to restore data in the working tree that Git can’t track, such as permissions data.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This hook can likewise validate the presence of files external to Git control that you may want copied in when the working tree changes.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `pre-push` hook runs during `git push`, after the remote refs have been updated but before any objects have been transferred.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It receives the name and location of the remote as parameters, and a list of to-be-updated refs through `stdin`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use it to validate a set of ref updates before a push occurs (a non-zero exit code will abort the push).
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Git occasionally does garbage collection as part of its normal operation, by invoking `git gc --auto`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `pre-auto-gc` hook is invoked just before the garbage collection takes place, and can be used to notify you that this is happening, or to abort the collection if now isn’t a good time.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] In addition to the client-side hooks, you can use a couple of important server-side hooks as a system administrator to enforce nearly any kind of policy for your project.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] These scripts run before and after pushes to the server.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The pre hooks can exit non-zero at any time to reject the push as well as print an error message back to the client; you can set up a push policy that’s as complex as you wish.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The first script to run when handling a push from a client is `pre-receive`.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It takes a list of references that are being pushed from stdin; if it exits non-zero, none of them are accepted.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] You can use this hook to do things like make sure none of the updated references are non-fast-forwards, or to do access control for all the refs and files they’re modifying with the push.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `update` script is very similar to the `pre-receive` script, except that it’s run once for each branch the pusher is trying to update.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If the pusher is trying to push to multiple branches, `pre-receive` runs only once, whereas `update` runs once per branch they’re pushing to.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Instead of reading from stdin, this script takes three arguments: the name of the reference (branch), the SHA-1 that reference pointed to before the push, and the SHA-1 the user is trying to push.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] If the `update` script exits non-zero, only that reference is rejected; other references can still be updated.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] The `post-receive` hook runs after the entire process is completed and can be used to update other services or notify users.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] It takes the same stdin data as the `pre-receive` hook.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] Examples include emailing a list, notifying a continuous integration server, or updating a ticket-tracking system – you can even parse the commit messages to see if any tickets need to be opened, modified, or closed.
[src:git-hooks/customizing-git-git-hooks] This script can’t stop the push process, but the client doesn’t disconnect until it has completed, so be careful if you try to do anything that may take a long time.
[src:git-hooks/git] Design goals of Git include speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows—thousands of parallel branches running on different computers.
[src:git-hooks/git] As with most other distributed version control systems, and unlike most client–server systems, Git maintains a local copy of the entire repository, also known as the "repo", with history and version-tracking abilities, independent of network access or a central server.
[src:git-hooks/git] A repository is stored on each computer in a standard directory with additional, hidden files to provide version control capabilities.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git provides features to synchronize changes between repositories that share history; for asynchronous collaboration, this extends to repositories on remote machines.
[src:git-hooks/git] Although all repositories (with the same history) are peers, developers often use a central server to host a repository to hold an integrated copy.
[src:git-hooks/git] Today, Git is the version control system most commonly used by software developers.
[src:git-hooks/git] It is the most popular distributed version control system, with nearly 95% of developers reporting it as their primary version control system as of 2022.
[src:git-hooks/git] It is the most widely used source-code management tool among professional developers.
[src:git-hooks/git] Several different software forges offer Git repository services, including GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git is free and open-source software shared under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:git-hooks/git] The trademark "Git" is registered by the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds started developing Git in April 2005 after the free license for BitKeeper, the proprietary source-control management (SCM) system used for Linux kernel development since 2002, was revoked for Linux.
[src:git-hooks/git] The copyright holder of BitKeeper, Larry McVoy, claimed that Andrew Tridgell had created SourcePuller by reverse engineering the BitKeeper protocols.
[src:git-hooks/git] The same incident also spurred the creation of Mercurial, another version-control system.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds wanted a distributed system that he could use like BitKeeper, but none of the available free systems met his needs.
[src:git-hooks/git] He cited an example of a source-control management system needing 30 seconds to apply a patch and update all associated metadata, and noted that this would not scale to the needs of Linux kernel development, where synchronizing with fellow maintainers could require 250 such actions at once.
[src:git-hooks/git] These criteria eliminated every version-control system in use at the time, so immediately after the 2.6.12-rc2 Linux kernel development release, Torvalds set out to write his own.
[src:git-hooks/git] The development of Git began on 3 April 2005.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds announced the project on 6 April and became self-hosting the next day.
[src:git-hooks/git] The first merge of multiple branches took place on 18 April.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds achieved his performance goals; on 29 April, the nascent Git was benchmarked recording patches to the Linux kernel tree at a rate of 6.7 patches per second.
[src:git-hooks/git] On 16 June, Git managed the kernel 2.6.12 release.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds turned over maintenance on 26 July 2005 to Junio Hamano, a major contributor to the project.
[src:git-hooks/git] Hamano was responsible for the 1.0 release on 21 December 2005.
[src:git-hooks/git] Torvalds quipped about the name *git* (which is British English slang for an unpleasant or silly person): "I'm an egotistical bastard, and I name all my projects after myself.
[src:git-hooks/git] First 'Linux', now 'git'." The man page describes Git as "the stupid content tracker".
[src:git-hooks/git] The source code for Git refers to the program as "the information manager from hell".
[src:git-hooks/git] Git's design is a synthesis of Torvalds's experience with Linux in maintaining a large distributed development project, along with his intimate knowledge of file-system performance gained from the same project and the urgent need to produce a working system in short order.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git supports rapid branching and merging, and includes specific tools for visualizing and navigating a non-linear development history.
[src:git-hooks/git] In Git, a core assumption is that a change will be merged more often than it is written, as it is passed around to various reviewers.
[src:git-hooks/git] In Git, branches are very lightweight: a branch is only a reference to one commit.
[src:git-hooks/git] , Git gives each developer a local copy of the full development history, and changes are copied from one such repository to another.
[src:git-hooks/git] These changes are imported as added development branches and can be merged in the same way as a locally developed branch.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git also has a CVS server emulation, which enables the use of existing CVS clients and IDE plugins to access Git repositories.
[src:git-hooks/git] repositories can be used directly with git-svn.
[src:git-hooks/git] ; fetching version history from a locally stored repository can be one hundred times faster than fetching it from the remote server.
[src:git-hooks/git] in Git terms) depends upon the complete development history leading up to that commit.
[src:git-hooks/git] Once it is published, it is not possible to change the old versions without it being noticed.
[src:git-hooks/git] , but with added data at the nodes and leaves.
[src:git-hooks/git] and several shell scripts that provide wrappers around those programs.
[src:git-hooks/git] Although most of those scripts have since been rewritten in C for speed and portability, the design remains, and it is easy to chain the components together.
[src:git-hooks/git] As part of its toolkit design, Git has a well-defined model of an incomplete merge, and it has multiple algorithms for completing it, culminating in telling the user that it is unable to complete the merge automatically and that manual editing is needed.
[src:git-hooks/git] Aborting operations or backing out changes will leave useless dangling objects in the database.
[src:git-hooks/git] These are generally a small fraction of the continuously growing history of wanted objects.
[src:git-hooks/git] when enough loose objects have been created in the repository.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git stores each newly created object as a separate file.
[src:git-hooks/git] Although individually compressed, this takes up a great deal of space and is inefficient.
[src:git-hooks/git] that files with the same name are probably similar, without depending on this for correctness.
[src:git-hooks/git] A corresponding index file is created for each packfile, recording the offset of each object in the packfile.
[src:git-hooks/git] Newly created objects (with newly added history) are still stored as single objects, and periodic repacking is needed to maintain space efficiency.
[src:git-hooks/git] The process of packing the repository can be very computationally costly.
[src:git-hooks/git] By allowing objects to exist in the repository in a loose but quickly generated format, Git allows the costly pack operation to be deferred until later, when time matters less, e.g., the end of a workday.
[src:git-hooks/git] inside, and the file name of the packfile also contains an SHA-1 checksum.
[src:git-hooks/git] Another property of Git is that it snapshots directory trees of files.
[src:git-hooks/git] The earliest systems for tracking versions of source code, Source Code Control System (SCCS) and Revision Control System (RCS), worked on individual files and emphasized the space savings to be gained from interleaved deltas (SCCS) or delta encoding (RCS) the (mostly similar) versions.
[src:git-hooks/git] Later revision-control systems maintained this notion of a file having an identity across multiple revisions of a project.
[src:git-hooks/git] However, Torvalds rejected this concept.
[src:git-hooks/git] Consequently, Git does not explicitly record file revision relationships at any level below the source-code tree.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git's primitives are not inherently a source-code management system.
[src:git-hooks/git] From this initial design approach, Git has developed the full set of features expected of a traditional SCM, with features mostly being created as needed, then refined and extended over time.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git has two data structures: a mutable *index* (also called *stage* or *cache*) that caches information about the working directory and the next revision to be committed; and an *object database* that stores immutable objects.
[src:git-hooks/git] The index serves as a connection point between the object database and the working tree.
[src:git-hooks/git] Each object is identified by a SHA-1 hash of its contents.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git computes the hash and uses this value for the object's name.
[src:git-hooks/git] The object is put into a directory matching the first two characters of its hash.
[src:git-hooks/git] The rest of the hash is used as the file name for that object.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git stores each revision of a file as a unique blob.
[src:git-hooks/git] The relationships between the blobs can be found through examining the tree and commit objects.
[src:git-hooks/git] Newly added objects are stored in their entirety using zlib compression.
[src:git-hooks/git] This can consume a large amount of disk space quickly, so objects can be combined into *packs*, which use delta compression to save space, storing blobs as their changes relative to other blobs.
[src:git-hooks/git] Additionally, Git stores labels called refs (short for references) to indicate the locations of various commits.
[src:git-hooks/git] A *.gitignore* file may be created in a Git repository as a plain text file.
[src:git-hooks/git] The files listed in the *.gitignore* file will *not* be tracked by Git.
[src:git-hooks/git] This feature can be used to ignore files with keys or passwords, various extraneous files, and large files (which GitHub will refuse to upload).
[src:git-hooks/git] Every object in the Git database that is not referred to may be cleaned up by using a garbage collection command or automatically.
[src:git-hooks/git] An object may be referenced by another object or an explicit reference.
[src:git-hooks/git] The commands to create, move, and delete references vary.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git (the main implementation in C) is primarily developed on Linux, although it also supports most major operating systems, including the BSDs (DragonFly BSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD), Solaris, macOS, and Windows.
[src:git-hooks/git] The first Windows port of Git was primarily a Linux-emulation framework that hosts the Linux version.
[src:git-hooks/git] Currently, native Windows builds of Git are distributed as 32- and 64-bit installers.
[src:git-hooks/git] The git official website currently maintains a build of Git for Windows, still using the MSYS2 environment.
[src:git-hooks/git] The JGit implementation of Git is a pure Java software library, designed to be embedded in any Java application.
[src:git-hooks/git] JGit is used in the Gerrit code-review tool, and in EGit, a Git client for the Eclipse IDE.
[src:git-hooks/git] Go-git is an open-source implementation of Git written in pure Go.
[src:git-hooks/git] It is currently used for backing projects as a SQL interface for Git code repositories and providing encryption for Git.
[src:git-hooks/git] Dulwich is an implementation of Git written in pure Python with support for CPython 3.6 and later and Pypy.
[src:git-hooks/git] The libgit2 implementation of Git is an ANSI C software library with no other dependencies, which can be built on multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, macOS, and BSD.
[src:git-hooks/git] It has bindings for many programming languages, including Ruby, Python, and Haskell.
[src:git-hooks/git] As Git is a distributed version control system, it could be used as a server out of the box.
[src:git-hooks/git] It is shipped with a built-in command `git daemon` which starts a simple TCP server running on the Git protocol.
[src:git-hooks/git] Dedicated Git HTTP servers help (amongst other features) by adding access control, displaying the contents of a Git repository via the web interfaces, and managing multiple repositories.
[src:git-hooks/git] Already existing Git repositories can be cloned and shared to be used by others as a centralized repo.
[src:git-hooks/git] It can also be accessed via remote shell just by having the Git software installed and allowing a user to log in.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git servers typically listen on TCP port 9418.
[src:git-hooks/git] For Web-based repository browsing, Git is also shipped with gitweb, a CGI-based interface for viewing repository contents over HTTP.
[src:git-hooks/git] There are many offerings of Git repositories as a service.
[src:git-hooks/git] The most popular are GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git GUI clients offer a graphical user interface (GUI) to simplify interaction with Git repositories.
[src:git-hooks/git] These GUIs provide visual representations of project history, including branches, commits, and file changes.
[src:git-hooks/git] They also streamline actions like staging changes, creating commits, and managing branches.
[src:git-hooks/git] Visual diff tools help resolve merge conflicts arising from concurrent development.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git comes with a Tcl/Tk GUI, which allows users to perform actions such as creating and amending commits, creating and merging branches, and interacting with remote repositories.
[src:git-hooks/git] In addition to the official GUI, many third-party interfaces exist that provide similar features to the official GUI distributed with Git.
[src:git-hooks/git] GUI clients make Git easier to learn and use, improving workflow efficiency and reducing errors.
[src:git-hooks/git] Open-source directory Open Hub reported a similar uptake among open-source projects.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git was the overwhelming favorite of responding developers in these surveys, reporting as high as 93.9% in 2022.
[src:git-hooks/git] The UK IT jobs website itjobswatch.co.uk reports that as of late September 2016, 29.27% of UK permanent software development job openings have cited Git, ahead of 12.17% for Microsoft Team Foundation Server, 10.60% for Subversion, 1.30% for Mercurial, and 0.48% for Visual SourceSafe.
[src:git-hooks/git] There are many *Git extensions*, like Git LFS, which started as an extension to Git in the GitHub community and is now widely used by other repositories.
[src:git-hooks/git] Extensions are usually independently developed and maintained by different people, but at some point in the future, a widely used extension can be merged with Git.
[src:git-hooks/git] Microsoft developed the Virtual File System for Git (VFS for Git; formerly Git Virtual File System or GVFS) extension to handle the size of the Windows source-code tree as part of their 2017 migration from Perforce.
[src:git-hooks/git] VFS for Git allows cloned repositories to use placeholders whose contents are downloaded only once a file is accessed.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git can be used in a variety of different ways, but some conventions are commonly adopted.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git does not provide access-control mechanisms, but was designed for operation with other tools that specialize in access control.
[src:git-hooks/git] On 17 December 2014, an exploit was found affecting the Windows and macOS versions of the Git client.
[src:git-hooks/git] An attacker could also modify the *.git/config* configuration file, which allows the attacker to create malicious Git aliases (aliases for Git commands or external commands) or modify extant aliases to execute malicious commands when run.
[src:git-hooks/git] The vulnerability was patched in version 2.2.1 of Git, released on 17 December 2014, and announced the next day.
[src:git-hooks/git] Git version 2.6.1, released on 29 September 2015, contained a patch for a security vulnerability (CVE-2015-7545) that allowed arbitrary code execution.
[src:git-hooks/git] The vulnerability was exploitable if an attacker could convince a victim to clone a specific URL, as the arbitrary commands were embedded in the URL.
[src:git-hooks/git] An attacker could use the exploit via a man-in-the-middle attack if the connection was unencrypted, as they could redirect the user to a URL of their choice.
[src:git-hooks/git] Recursive clones were also vulnerable, since they allowed the controller of a repository to specify arbitrary URLs via the gitmodules file.
[src:git-hooks/git] Linus Torvalds has responded that the hash was mostly to guard against accidental corruption, and the security a cryptographically secure hash gives was just an accidental side effect, with the main security being signing elsewhere.
[src:git-hooks/git] Since a demonstration of the SHAttered attack against Git in 2017, Git was modified to use an SHA-1 variant resistant to this attack.
[src:git-hooks/git] A plan for hash function transition is being written since February 2020.
[src:git-hooks/git] "Git" is a registered word trademark of Software Freedom Conservancy, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office as Registration Number 4680534 since 2015-02-03.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] In computer programming, **hooking** is a range of techniques used to alter or augment the behaviour of an operating system, of applications, or of other software components by intercepting function calls or messages or events passed between software components.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Code that handles such intercepted function calls, events or messages is called a **hook**.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Hook methods are of particular importance in the template method pattern where common code in an abstract class can be augmented by custom code in a subclass.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] In this case each hook method is defined in the abstract class with an empty implementation which then allows a different implementation to be supplied in each concrete subclass.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Hooking is used for many purposes, including debugging and extending functionality.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Examples might include intercepting keyboard or mouse event messages before they reach an application, or intercepting operating system calls in order to monitor behavior or modify the function of an application or other component.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] It is also widely used in benchmarking programs, for example frame rate measuring in 3D games, where the output and input is done through hooking.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Hooking can also be used by malicious code.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] For example, rootkits, pieces of software that try to make themselves invisible by faking the output of API calls that would otherwise reveal their existence, often use hooking techniques.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Typically hooks are inserted while software is already running, but hooking is a tactic that can also be employed prior to the application being started.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Both these techniques are described in greater detail below.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Hooking can be achieved by modifying the source of the executable or library before an application is running, through techniques of reverse engineering.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] This is typically used to intercept function calls to either monitor or replace them entirely.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] For example, by using a disassembler, the entry point of a function within a module can be found.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] It can then be altered to instead dynamically load some other library module and then have it execute desired methods within that loaded library.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] If applicable, another related approach by which hooking can be achieved is by altering the import table of an executable.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] This table can be modified to load any additional library modules as well as changing what external code is invoked when a function is called by the application.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] An alternative method for achieving function hooking is by intercepting function calls through a wrapper library.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] A wrapper is a version of a library that an application loads, with all the same functionality of the original library that it will replace.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] That is, all the functions that are accessible are essentially the same between the original and the replacement.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] This wrapper library can be designed to call any of the functionality from the original library, or replace it with an entirely new set of logic.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The GNU Linker supports the `--wrap=foo` CLI option.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] When used, the linker replaces all calls to `foo` with calls to `__wrap_foo`.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The original definition of `foo` can now be referenced with the symbol `__real_foo`.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Since this method does not use the dynamic linker, this method can only be used when a program's source code is available and the linking step of the build can be modified.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Operating systems and software may provide the means to easily insert event hooks at runtime.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] It is available provided that the process inserting the hook is granted enough permission to do so.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Microsoft Windows for example, allows users to insert hooks that can be used to process or modify system events and application events for dialogs, scrollbars, and menus as well as other items.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] It also allows a hook to insert, remove, process or modify keyboard and mouse events.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Linux provides another example where hooks can be used in a similar manner to process network events within the kernel through NetFilter.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] When such functionality is not provided, a special form of hooking employs intercepting the library function calls made by a process.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Function hooking is implemented by changing the very first few code instructions of the target function to jump to an injected code.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Alternatively on systems using the shared library concept, the interrupt vector table or the import descriptor table can be modified in memory.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Essentially these tactics employ the same ideas as those of source modification, but instead altering instructions and structures located in the memory of a process once it is already running.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Whenever a class defines/inherits a virtual function (or method), compilers add a hidden member variable to the class which points to a virtual method table (VMT or Vtable).
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Most compilers place the hidden VMT pointer at the first 4 bytes of every instance of the class.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] A VMT is basically an array of pointers to all the virtual functions that instances of the class may call.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] At runtime these pointers are set to point to the right functions, because at compile time, it is not yet known if the base function is to be called or if an overridden version of the function from a derived class is to be called (thereby allowing for polymorphism).
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Therefore, virtual functions can be hooked by replacing the pointers to them within any VMT that they appear.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The code below shows an example of a typical VMT hook in Microsoft Windows, written in C++.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] All virtual functions must be class member functions, and all (non-static) class member functions are called with the __thiscall calling convention (unless the member function takes a variable number of arguments, in which case it is called with __cdecl).
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The __thiscall calling convention passes a pointer to the calling class instance (commonly referred to as a "this" pointer) via the ECX register (on the x86 architecture).
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Therefore, in order for a hook function to properly intercept the "this" pointer that is passed and take it as an argument, it must look into the ECX register.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] In the above example, this is done by setting the hook function (hkVirtualFn1) to use the __fastcall calling convention, which causes the hook function to look into the ECX register for one of its arguments.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Also note that, in the above example, the hook function (hkVirtualFn1) is not a member function itself so it cannot use the __thiscall calling convention. __fastcall has to be used instead because it is the only other calling convention that looks into the ECX register for an argument.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The following example will hook into keyboard events in Microsoft Windows using the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The following source code is an example of an API/function hooking method which hooks by overwriting the first six bytes of a destination function with a JMP instruction to a new function.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The code is compiled into a DLL file then loaded into the target process using any method of DLL injection.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] Using a backup of the original function one might then restore the first six bytes again so the call will not be interrupted.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] In this example the win32 API function MessageBoxW is hooked.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] This example shows how to use hooking to alter network traffic in the Linux kernel using Netfilter.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The following code demonstrates how to hook functions that are imported from another module.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] This can be used to hook functions in a different process from the calling process.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] For this the code must be compiled into a DLL file then loaded into the target process using any method of DLL injection.
[src:git-hooks/hooking] The advantage of this method is that it is less detectable by antivirus software and/or anti-cheat software, one might make this into an external hook that doesn't make use of any malicious calls.
